1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,359
This is the ElevenLabs version. The same video exists voiced by Suno — the link is in the description. You are the blind test.

2
00:00:08,359 --> 00:00:21,759
Every video in this series speaks. And until today, every word of it cost ElevenLabs credits. This is the cost test: the same narration, voiced two different ways — and the video you're watching is the experiment.

3
00:00:21,759 --> 00:00:34,189
Here's the itch. ElevenLabs is metered. Every character of every beat, every retake, every regeneration draws down the same tank. It's a great voice — but a series that talks a lot pays a lot.

4
00:00:34,189 --> 00:00:50,310
The challenger is Suno. My voice lives there too — uploaded once. It leans a little speak-song, but for spoken word it's clear. And the pricing shape is different: not a meter, a flat generation — and one generation can carry an entire video's narration.

5
00:00:50,310 --> 00:01:07,680
So the toolkit grew a second voice path. Art suno takes the same beat sheet — the single source of truth — and writes the narration out as text files, one per four thousand characters, because that's the size of Suno's lyrics box. No beat is ever split across a file boundary.

6
00:01:07,680 --> 00:01:23,510
Every beat gets one meta tag above it: spoken word. Not once at the top — above every single beat. Because even when your only style note is spoken word, Suno will sometimes decide your sentence deserves a melody. The tag keeps it speaking.

7
00:01:23,510 --> 00:01:37,980
The human loop is three moves. Paste a file into Suno. Generate with your voice and download the vocal-only stem — no music bed. Then drop it in the pantry. The pantry is where human-made media always lands in this toolkit.

8
00:01:37,980 --> 00:01:53,290
Then art suno-slice cuts the stem at the silences between beats — one mp3 per beat — and measures every one. If the segments don't match the beats, it refuses to touch anything and tells you which knob to turn. No quiet failures.

9
00:01:53,290 --> 00:02:12,180
And here's the part that matters. The slices land in exactly the slots ElevenLabs would have filled. Same files, same measured durations, same beat sheet. Downstream — the renders, the captions, the shorts, the publish — nothing knows which engine spoke. The voice is a plug.

10
00:02:12,180 --> 00:02:30,600
The exact numbers from this build are on screen — what this video's narration cost through the meter, and what it cost flat. The shape of the answer was never in doubt: metered pricing scales with how much you talk. Flat pricing doesn't. A talkative series feels that difference on every single video.

11
00:02:30,600 --> 00:02:45,880
It isn't a free lunch. The metered voice is steadier — take after take sounds the same. The flat voice can drift musical, and you pay in retakes and slicing instead of credits. Cheap has a workflow tax. The question is whether the tax is smaller than the bill.

12
00:02:45,880 --> 00:03:03,380
So here's the split, one more time. The machine will voice every beat either way — meter or flat, it doesn't care. What it can't do is decide what you're willing to sound like. I listened to both takes of this very video. One of them is playing right now — because I picked it. You bring the taste.

13
00:03:03,380 --> 00:03:14,140
And all of it — every generation, every credit, every retake — is in one honest log. Two engines, one narration, real numbers. This video was built from that log.

14
00:03:14,140 --> 00:03:26,810
That's the cost test. Subscribe to follow the series, and find the whole toolkit at www dot brutalist dot art. You bring the taste; the machine brings the hands — and now, either voice.
